      "title": "Michael Clarke: WATCH: When Michael Clarke drove an auto-rickshaw",
      "text": "NEW DELHI: Former Australia cricketer Michael Clarke is currently in India officiating as a commentator in the ongoing four-Test Border-Gavaskar Trophy between India and Australia.\nAustralia defeated India in the series opener in Pune and are now gearing up for the second Test to be played in Bangalore. With a few days left before the action resumes, Clarke took some time off and tried his hand mastering on driving an auto-rickshaw in Bengaluru.\nClarke shared a 22-second video on his official Facebook page in which he can be seen driving the famous auto-rickshaw or as the foreigners call it 'tuk-tuk'.\nHe captioned the video, \"Mastered the art of driving the tuk tuk. Nice to be back in Bengaluru where it all started.\"\nThe 35-year-old made his Test debut in Bangalore in 2004 and went on to have a storied career that also saw him succeeding Ricky Ponting as the captain. In all, he played 115 Tests scoring 8643 runs with the help of 28 centuries and 27 fifties at 49.10.\nThe Steve Smith-led Australia humiliated India in the first Test at Pune, defeating the hosts by 333 runs. Left-arm spinner Steve O'Keefe spun the visitors to a dominating win claiming 12 wickets for 70 runs, the best ever match figures by a visiting spinner in India.\nBoth teams are set to clash in the second Test at M Chinnaswamy Stadium beginning Saturday.",
