      "title": "India vs Australia: How good are hosts’ batsmen against spin? Pune Test busted the myth",
      "text": "India vs Australia: How good are hosts' batsmen against spin? Pune Test busted the myth Rajesh Tiwary Feb, 28 2017 08:37:11 IST #Australia #Australia in india 2017 #Cricket #Dean elgar #India #Kevin pietersen #Michael clarke #Monty panesar #Nathan lyon #Pitch #Pune #Rangana herath #Shane warne #Sports #Steve o'keefe #Steven smith \nTeam India’s cheerleading squad, also sometimes referred to as television commentators are often heard gushing about Indian batsmen’s ability to play spin. Oh, the spinners have never troubled us much they would say, recounting an anecdote or two about Shane Warne getting rendered ineffective on these shores. \nThe plural of anecdote is not data though. A closer look at the numbers would show that while our batsmen have mostly been better than the touring teams, the dominance against spin is far from what we were used to seeing in the 1990s. Australia's Steve O'Keefe celebrates getting Virat Kohli's wicket in the 2nd innings of Pune Test. AP \nThe current team has enjoyed a season of unprecedented home dominance over the past two years. While Indian batsmen have made merry on flatter surfaces, the numbers are far from flattering whenever they have played on rank turners like the ones at Mohali and Nagpur in 2015 against South Africa and at Pune against Australia in 2017 with scores of 201, 200, 215, 173, 105 and 107. \nIt’s easy to dismiss batting against spin on some of these minefields as a game of Russian Roulette where you just ride your luck, but as touring batsmen like Steve Smith and Kevin Pietersen have demonstrated, there are methods to improve your odds of success. \nCricket stats analysis engine, Cricviz showed that Australians played and missed 50 times in their second innings and 44 in their first, a number substantially higher than an average inning of the same duration. While an ignorant observer will view this as lady luck smiling on the tourists, a nuanced view will show that this was part of a practised plan. Australian batsmen played and missed at 50 balls in their innings! #INDvAUS \n— The Cricket Prof. (@CricProf) February 25, 2017 \nWhile Kevin Pietersen had planned to get rid of the close-in fielders by attacking the spinners, Smith, in his own words, eliminated one-half of the bat by playing the line and not the turn. The idea is to rule out certain modes of dismissal and finding percentage shots to score your runs. \nSmith was also happy to go down the pitch not only as a run-scoring option but also to disturb spinners’ lengths and could go back to defend whenever the length was even slightly short. As Damien Martyn showed in 2004, a strong back foot game against spin can bring you success on these pitches. \nOver the years, we have seen a pattern where Indian batsmen have struggled against left-arm spinners, especially of the quickish variety. Australia discovered it in Mumbai in 2004 when Indian batsmen were able to negotiate Nathan Hauritz comfortably, but Michael Clarke who hadn’t bowled at all in the match took six wickets for nine runs in a spell of six overs to skittle India in their second innings. Monty Panesar was the chief architect of India’s defeat in 2012 against England and Steve O'Keefe surprised many including himself with astonishing returns in Pune. Even a part-timer like Dean Elgar seemed more effective with his left arm spin at Mohali in 2015 than specialist South African spinners, Simon Harmer and Imran Tahir. At Galle in 2015, India surrendered to Rangana Herath, getting all out for 112 in the fourth innings. \nVarious explanations have been given for this apparent decline in India’s ability to play spin. A modern Indian batsman doesn’t have the same kind of exposure to quality spin on turning pitches at the first class level as the batsmen of yore. Once famous for running down the pitch at the slightest invitation against spin to open several scoring options, they now try to lunge back and forward from the crease. \nIn 2000, when Indian batsmen were struggling against Nicky Boje’s left arm spin on a fourth-inning pitch at Bangalore, Mohammad Azharuddin showed the way with a classy hundred. In one of his interviews, he demonstrated how he can defend with a closed face to negate the chance of nicking it to slip. \nOn a turning pitch, a left arm spinner or a leg spinner would generally try to pitch it within the line of the stumps. While MCC coaching manual would teach you to try and play with the spin as much as possible, if you can reach to the pitch of anything that is pitched on leg or middle, a wristy punch can open up the whole leg side. Think of VVS Laxman against Warne. Of course, it takes years of practice to develop the skill before you can do it against a high-quality international spinner and it requires really nimble feet when the bowlers are not giving it much air on a pitch that is turning square. \nIndia may do themselves a favour by not preparing any more pitches that resemble Pune or Nagpur. As the England series proved, Ashwin and Jadeja have enough guile to deceive batsmen even on a good batting wicket and their batsmen can use the friendly conditions to score big and score quickly to give them enough time to dismiss the opposition twice.",
